The UNICEF database demonstrates which countries lead the list in preparing women for marriage. The dashboard presents marriage readiness data through maps and trends while allowing users to check results between nations. The system tracks how nations evolve in marriage readiness over time to involve people better while capturing their reactions. The system displays data at several levels to build one informational story about women empowerment worldwide and data-driven problem assessment. The quality of public sharing depends on how analysis connects with design decisions and elements.

BAR GRAPH

Code 
import polars as pl
import pandas as pd
from plotnine import *

# Load dataset
df = pd.read_csv("/content/unicef_indicator_1.csv")

# Convert the pandas DataFrame to a Polars DataFrame
df_pl = pl.from_pandas(df)

# Step 1: Filter for the latest year (2023)
df_2023 = df_pl.filter(pl.col("time_period") == 2023)

# Step 2: Sort DataFrame by 'obs_value' in descending order
df_sorted = df_2023.sort("obs_value", descending=True).to_pandas()

# Step 3: Create a bar chart visualization using plotnine
bar_chart = (ggplot(data=df_sorted)
  + aes(x="country", y="obs_value", fill="obs_value")  # Add 'fill' to color bars based on 'obs_value'
  + geom_col()  # Create the bar chart
  + scale_fill_gradient(low="lightblue", high="steelblue")  # Gradient color from light to dark
  + labs(title="UNICEF Indicator 2023: Country Observations",
         x="Country",
         y="Observed Value",
         fill="Observed Value")  # Add legend title for the color gradient
  + theme_minimal()  # Apply theme
  + theme(
        axis_text_x=element_text(rotation=60, ha='right'),  # Rotate x-axis labels
        figure_size=(10, 6),  # Increase figure size for better readability
        plot_title=element_text(size=14, weight='bold')  # Enhance title readability
    )
)

# Display the plot
print(bar_chart)
bar_chart.draw()
<ggplot: (1000 x 600)>

SCATTER PLOT

Code 
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

# Load the data
df = pd.read_csv("unicef_indicator_1.csv")

# Filter for 2023
df_2023 = df[df["time_period"] == 2023]

# Use 'GDP' if it exists, otherwise use 'country'
x_variable = "GDP" if "GDP" in df_2023.columns else "country"
x_label = "GDP Per Capita ($)" if x_variable == "GDP" else "Country"

# Convert 'GDP' to numeric if used
if x_variable == "GDP":
    df_2023[x_variable] = pd.to_numeric(df_2023[x_variable], errors="coerce")

# Drop missing values
df_2023 = df_2023.dropna(subset=[x_variable, "obs_value"])

# Set up the scatterplot
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.scatterplot(x=df_2023[x_variable], y=df_2023["obs_value"], color="steelblue", alpha=0.7)

# Add regression line if 'GDP' is used
if x_variable == "GDP":
    sns.regplot(x=df_2023[x_variable], y=df_2023["obs_value"], scatter=False, color="red")

# Improve labels and styling
plt.xticks(rotation=90 if x_variable == "country" else 0)
plt.title(f"UNICEF Indicator 1: Observation Value vs. {x_label} (2023)", fontsize=14, fontweight="bold")
plt.xlabel(x_label, fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel("Observed Value", fontsize=12)
plt.grid(True)

# Show the plot
plt.show()

TIME SERIES CHART

Code 
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

# Load the dataset
df = pd.read_csv("unicef_indicator_1.csv")

# Step 1: Ensure necessary columns exist
required_columns = {"time_period", "obs_value"}
if not required_columns.issubset(df.columns):
    print("Error: Missing required columns! Available columns:", df.columns)
else:
    # Step 2: Aggregate data (if needed) and sort by time period
    df_time_series = df.groupby("time_period")["obs_value"].mean().reset_index()
    df_time_series = df_time_series.sort_values(by="time_period")

    # Step 3: Plot time-series chart
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
    sns.lineplot(x=df_time_series["time_period"], y=df_time_series["obs_value"], marker="o", color="blue")

    # Step 4: Improve labels and styling
    plt.title("UNICEF Indicator 1 Trend Over Time", fontsize=14, fontweight="bold")
    plt.xlabel("Year", fontsize=12)
    plt.ylabel("Observed Value", fontsize=12)
    plt.grid(True)

    # Step 5: Show the plot
    plt.show()

WORLD MAP

Code 
import pandas as pd
import geopandas as gpd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Step 1: Load the world shapefile
shape_world = gpd.read_file("https://public.opendatasoft.com/api/explore/v2.1/catalog/datasets/world-administrative-boundaries/exports/shp")
print("World shapefile loaded successfully!")

# Step 2: Load the dataset (unicef_indicator_1.csv)
df = pd.read_csv("unicef_indicator_1.csv")
print("Dataset loaded successfully!")

# Step 3: Rename the 'country' column in the dataset to match the 'name' column in the world shapefile
df.rename(columns={"country": "name"}, inplace=True)

# Step 4: Merge the dataset with the world shapefile
# Use 'left' join to retain all countries in the shapefile
shape_gapminder_code = shape_world.merge(df, on="name", how="left")
print("Merged GeoDataFrame successfully!")

# Step 5: Plot the full world map with increased size
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(50, 30))  # Increased size (width=50, height=30)
shape_gapminder_code.plot(
    column="obs_value",  # Replace "obs_value" with the column you want to visualize
    cmap="YlOrRd",  # Yellow to Red gradient
    linewidth=0.8,
    edgecolor="black",
    legend=True,
    ax=ax
)

# Step 6: Add country names as annotations
for x, y, label in zip(
    shape_gapminder_code.geometry.centroid.x,  # Longitude
    shape_gapminder_code.geometry.centroid.y,  # Latitude
    shape_gapminder_code["name"]  # Country names
):
    if not pd.isna(label):  # Only annotate countries with valid names
        ax.text(x, y, label, fontsize=8, ha="center", color="black")  # Adjust font size for better visibility

# Step 7: Improve styling and labels
plt.title("World Map: Observation Value by Country", fontsize=24, fontweight="bold")  # Larger title font size
plt.axis("off")  # Hide axis for a cleaner look

# Step 8: Show the map
plt.show()
